6193941e-fc53-435f-8af3-d7714167882e.59822b56-0837-41a2-b581-e6ba52edddee.description=
Accepts an object in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON) and
returns a value for the specified key.

The JSON format encodes objects as a set of unordered key/value pairs, which is
similar to a structure or map in other programming languages.  For example,
   { "city" \: "Palo Alto", 
     "state" \: "CA" }
is an object with two elements one with the name "city" having the value "Palo
Alto", and the other being the name "state" with the value "CA". This operation would 
return "Palo Alto" if user enters "city" as a key.

If the input object contains JSON array, array index can be used in the key input. For example, 
{ "location"\: [
      {"city"\: "Roseville", "country"\: "United States"},
      {"city"\: "Cluj", "country"\: "Romania"},
      {"city"\: "Yehud", "country"\: "Israel"}]    
}
The operation would return "Roseville" if user enters "location[0].city" as a key.

JavaScript objects are useful for representing structured data, and are
especially when used within an array.  For example, an operation that retrieves
a set of incidents from an external system may return the entire list in one
array of incident objects.  The description of the enclosing folder,
/Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and
the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org.

Inputs

   object
      The JavaScript object.  
      The operation will return a failure if it is not a JavaScript object.

   key
      The key in the object to get the value of.

Responses

   success
      The value was successfully returned for the specified key. 

   failure
      There was some error in processing the object, most likely because the
      object is not in valid JavaScript Object Notation or the specified key does not exist in the object.  
      You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with
      JavaScript Object Notation.

Outputs

   The primary output will be the value for the specified key in the object.

Note

    If the value in JSON object is in scientific notation, the returned output will be converted to an equivalent decimal number. Ex, 2.9e+1 will be converted to 29.
6193941e-fc53-435f-8af3-d7714167882e.769c3d04-3529-4776-a87b-24ae3e184db7.description=
Executes a Shell command(s) on the remote machine using the SSH protocol.

Inputs\:
    host - The hostname/IP address of the remote machine.
    port - The port number for SSH protocol.
Default value\: 22
    username - Name of the account on the remote machine.
    password - The password for the username. When using a private key file or a private key string, this input will be used as the passphrase for the file or string. For security reasons it is recommend to provide this input and protect the private key when using the 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs.
    proxyHost - The proxy server used to access the remote machine.
    proxyPort - The proxy server port. Default\: 8080. Valid values\: -1 and numbers greater than 0.
    proxyUsername - The user name used when connecting to the proxy.
    proxyPassword - The proxy server password associated with the proxyUsername input value.
    privateKeyFile - Path to private key file (OpenSSH type) on the machine where is the worker. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    privateKeyData – A string representing the private key (OpenSSH type) used for authenticating the user. This string is usually the content of a private key file. The 'privateKeyData' and the 'privateKeyFile' inputs are mutually exclusive. For security reasons it is recommend that the private key be protected by a passphrase that should be provided through the 'password' input.
    knownHostsPolicy - The policy used for managing known_hosts file. We recommend to use a "strict" policy so as to verify the host key against a local file containing known, trustworthy machines. If you choose "allow" or "add" policy then you will connect to the server without any verification. If there is a Man-In-The-Middle attack then you will be connected to a fake server and the SSH commands that you send will go through that fake server. 
Valid values\:  
allow\=It will permit the connection to any hosts. 
strict\=It will permit the connection only to the hosts specified in known_hosts file. 
add\=It will permit the connection to any hosts, if the host is not in the known_hosts file it will be added. 
Default value\: strict
    command - The command(s) to execute.
    characterSet - The characterSet name for input stream encoding from the remote machine.
Examples\: SJIS, EUC-JP, UTF-8
Default value\: UTF-8
    pty - Whether to use a pseudo-terminal (PTY) session.
Valid values\: false, true 
Default value\: false
    timeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the command to complete.
Default value\: 90000
    connectTimeout - Time in milliseconds to wait for the connection to be made.
Default value\: 10000
    closeSession - If true it closes the SSH session at completion of this operation. If false the SSH session will be cached for future calls of this operation during the life of the flow.
Valid values\: false, true 
Default value\: false
    useGlobalContext -  Specifies whether to enable the session sharing into the subflows.
Valid values\: false, true 
Default value\: false

Results\:
    returnResult - The result of the command (STDOUT is success, otherwise STDERR).
    STDERR - The standard error of the command.
    STDOUT - The standard output of the command.
    exitStatus - The exit status of the remote command corresponding to the SSH channel. The exit status is only available for certain types of channels, and only after the channel was closed (more exactly, just before the channel is closed).
Examples\: 0 for a successful command, -1 if the command was not yet terminated (or this channel type has no command), 126 if the command cannot execute.
    TimedOut - Is set to "true" if the value set in the "timeout" input has elapsed and the command timed out.

Responses\:
    success - The command was executed successfully.
    failure - The command could not be executed or if the command was not yet terminated.

Notes\:
1. If the SSH session is cached then only the connection is kept and not the context (variables) represented by SSH channel.
2. Hidden inputs\:
    knownHostsPath -  Specifies the path to the known_hots file on the running server.
Default value\: /.ssh/known_hosts
Examples\: /home/admin/.ssh/known_hosts
   allowExpectCommands - Specifies whether to allow the execution of expect like commands. Some protocols ( like OGFS ) do not work for regular commands if this behavior is enabled. The recommended operation to use for expect like commands is SSH Shell.
Default value\: false
3. In order to use private keys with different encryption types (ex.\: aes256-cbc) needs to be updated the /java/lib/security/local_policy.jar JAR file with one that accept all security policies (ex.\: http\://www.oracle.com/technetwork/java/javase/downloads/jce-7-download-432124.html). After update you must restart the Studio or Central service.
4. The "timeout" input refers only to the command timeout and it's not linked with any kind of connection timeout. The "commandTimedOut" output shows if the command timed out and doesn't interfere with the returnResult, STDERR or STDOUT outputs, so even if the command times out these outputs will still be populated accordingly.
5. The operation supports connections through HTTP proxy with username and password authentication.

6193941e-fc53-435f-8af3-d7714167882e.9bd47021-0dac-4d47-be93-2c32596ce6c5.description=
This operation writes the data from "contents" input to the requested file. The operation can be used to overwrite existing content of the file, append extra lines to it or even create a new file.

Inputs\:
    source -  Full path to file. If the file does not exist it is created first.
    contents - The content that should be written to the file. This input field can contain more lines, separated by a delimiter. If it contains the new line character (\n or \r\n), but this is not the delimiter, this character will be escaped and written to file.  
Example\: "This is line no. 01\nThis is line no. 2\n" where \n is the delimiter.
    delimiter - Specifies the newline delimiter that is used to split the "contents" input field into separate lines that will be further written to the given file.
Examples\: \n, \r\n, etc
    characterSet - The character encoding used to write to the file. 
Default\: UTF-8. 
Valid values\: windows-1252, UTF-16, UTF-16BE,  ISO-8859-1, US-ASCII, Shift_JIS etc.
    overwrite - Specifies whether to overwrite the file or append to it. 
Default\: true. 
Valid values\: true, false or the empty string. If this is left empty, the file will be overwritten.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the "success" confirmation message if the operation successfully completes, or an exception message otherwise.
    returnCode - It has the value 0 if the operation successfully completes and 1 otherwise.
    exception - This contains an exception message if the operation fails.

Responses\:
    success - File/directory was written successfully.
    failure - Unable to write to file/directory, empty contents or source.

Examples\:
1. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Windows\:
    source\: C\:\Program Files\example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,

2. This is a valid input example for using this operation on Linux\:
    source\: /root/example.txt
    contents\: line1,line2,line3
    delimiter\: ,
6193941e-fc53-435f-8af3-d7714167882e.ba91d75c-3420-4895-9f26-4caf97f1f931.description=This operation iterates through a string that contains an array in the JavaScript Object Notation format (JSON). Each time this operation is called, it places the value of the current array element into the "returnResult" output and advances the iterator to the next array element. The JSON format is used to encode arrays and other values using JavaScript notation. For arrays, this means that the values need to be enclosed by square brackets, and each element in the array can be a string (enclosed by quotes), a number, true, false, null, or nested array or object. Commas are always used as delimiters between array elements, and they can also appear within string elements. The benefits of JavaScript arrays are that delimiters are fixed and cannot be confused with data, and that complex nesting of arrays and objects are supported. The description of the enclosing folder, /Library/Utility Operations/Container/JavaScript Objects has more examples, and the JSON format is described completely at http\://www.json.org. Inputs\: array - The JavaScript array that will be iterated through. A normal OO list is NOT a JavaScript array. Examples\: For example, the following is a simple JSON array\: [ "cat", "dog", "horse" ] The equivalent OO list (that is not a JavaScript array) is\: cat,dog,horse Results\: returnResult - This is the primary output and contains the current array element or an exception message if something went wrong. When incorporating this operation into a flow, you should assign a meaningful result value from this field. Result - This output field contains the value from the "returnResult" field. Responses\: has more - The iterator has not yet reached the end of the array. The "returnResult" output will be populated with the value of the current element in the array, and the iterator will advance to the next element in the array. no more - The iterator has reached the end of the array, and there is no more data to return. The iterator will become undefined after this call, which basically will reset it so that if called again, this operation will begin another iteration at the beginning of the array. failure - There was some error in iterating through the list, and the "returnResult" output will contain information about the error. This will occur if the input array is not a valid JavaScript array. You may wish to use a tool such as http\://www.jsonlint.com/ to help diagnose problems with JavaScript Object Notation. Notes\: 1. Modifying the contents of the array during iteration is not generally supported, but will be safe as long as the affected item(s) are beyond the current position of the iterator. The iterator keeps track of where it is in the array by position. If items are added or removed to the list in a position preceding the iterator, it may cause the iterator to return results that are not obvious. For example, if the array contains [ "a", "b", "c" ] and the iterator is positioned on the second element, "b" and the first element is removed, then the iterator will now be at the last element in the list, "c". 2. There is currently a limitation that a flow can only have one of these array iterator steps active at a time without causing possible conflicts. In other words, if you need to iterate through a nested array, you should use a sub-flow to process the inner array. You may have two or more of these array iterators in the same flow as long as each iterator reaches the end of its array before the next one begins. 3. Note that since JavaScript arrays may contain nested arrays or other objects, the value returned in "returnResult" field may also require further processing. 6193941e-fc53-435f-8af3-d7714167882e.f0c25dd9-5066-4aa9-947b-ad6fef59118b.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The the value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);
